# Convolution is associative.

Continuous case:
\begin{equation*}
((f\star g)\star h)(t) =\int_0^t(f\star g)(s)h(t-s)\,ds\\
=\int_{0}^t\left(\int_{0}^sf(u)g(s-u)\,du\right)h(t-s)\,ds\\
=\int_{s=0}^t\int_{u=0}^sf(u)g(s-u)h(t-s)\,du\,ds\\
=\int_{u=0}^t\int_{s=u}^tf(u)g(s-u)h(t-s)\,ds\,du\\
=\int_{u=0}^t\int_{s=0}^{t-u}f(u)g(s)h(t-s-u)\,ds\,du\\
=\int_{u=0}^tf(u)\left(\int_{s=0}^{t-u}g(s)h(t-u-s)\,ds\right)\,du\\
=\int_{u=0}^tf(u)(g\star h)(t-u)\,du\\
=(f\star (g\star h))(t)
\end{equation*}

Discrete case: 
\begin{equation*}
((f\star g)\star h)(n) =\sum_{k=0}^n(f\star g)(k)h(n-k)\\
=\sum_{k=0}^n\sum_{l=0}^kf(l)g(k-l)h(n-k)\\
=\sum_{l=0}^n\sum_{k=l}^nf(l)g(k-l)h(n-k)\\
=\sum_{l=0}^n\sum_{k=0}^{n-l}f(l)g(k)h(n-k-l)\\
=\sum_{l=0}^nf(l)(g\star h)(n-l)\\
=(f\star(g\star h))(n)
\end{equation*}

# Correlation is not associative.

Continuous case:
\begin{equation*}
((f\circ g)\circ h)(t) =\int_0^t(f\circ g)(s)h(s+t)\,ds\\
=\int_{0}^t\left(\int_{0}^sf(u)g(u+s)\,du\right)h(s+t)\,ds\\
=\int_{s=0}^t\int_{u=0}^sf(u)g(u+s)h(s+t)\,du\,ds\\
=\int_{u=0}^t\int_{s=u}^tf(u)g(u+s)h(s+t)\,ds\,du\\
=\int_{u=0}^t\int_{s=0}^{t-u}f(u)g(s+2u)h(s+u+t)\,ds\,du\\
=\int_{0}^tf(u)\left(\int_{0}^{t-u}g(s+2u)h(s+u+t)\,ds\right)\,du\\
\end{equation*}

\begin{equation*}
(f\circ (g\circ h))(t) =\int_0^t f(u)(g\circ h)(u+t)\,du\\
=\int_0^t f(u)\left(\int_0^{u+t}g(s)h(s+u+t)\,ds\right)\,du\\
\end{equation*}

# Convolution complexity

Complexity: $(MN)^2(H-M+1)(W-N+1)$

Complexity using FFT: $MNlog(MN)(H-M+1)(W-N+1)$

# Speed up convolution

Since we have
$g(x,y) = \frac{1}{2\pi \sigma ^2}exp(\frac{-(x^2 + y^2)}{2\sigma^2}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi} \sigma_x ^2}exp(\frac{-x^2}{2\sigma_x^2}) \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi} \sigma_y ^2}exp(\frac{-y^2}{2\sigma_y^2})$,
multiplication in frequency domain yields convolution in time domain. Now our linear filter is separated into two subsequent convolutions which is much faster than the big filter.

